              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3749175964602153058">I read this as research of the Vikings but I am rather disappointed. I will stick to the Saga&apos;s and archaeological sources...<br/><br/>A difficult read in more ways than one. I struggled to understand which part of the world they were visiting and what people they were describing. Google could not help me with some of the medieval Arabic names. <br/>The stories were contradictory, not only between the different travellers but within each one and archaeological sources. For instance: the rus lived in a country </span>
  <span id="freeText3749175964602153058" style="display:none">I read this as research of the Vikings but I am rather disappointed. I will stick to the Saga's and archaeological sources...<br /><br />A difficult read in more ways than one. I struggled to understand which part of the world they were visiting and what people they were describing. Google could not help me with some of the medieval Arabic names. <br />The stories were contradictory, not only between the different travellers but within each one and archaeological sources. For instance: the rus lived in a country with no fruit nor trees (I wonder how they built their ships.) The next traveller mentioned that they came from a land of dense forests.<br />One described them as hospitable and friendly, the next claimed that all strangers that entered their land were killed.<br />I found some inconsistencies compared to archaeological findings that make me sceptical to the rest that is written. <br /><br />I do not recommend for those who are seeking information about Vikings. I have no knowledge of the routes of the merchants mentioned and cannot comment on the other parts of the book.<br /><br />2020-51</span>
