<div id="review_3203819585" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3203819585" />
    <a title="Miike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4980553-miike"><img alt="Miike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1297732722p2/4980553.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3203819585?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Miike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Miike" href="/user/show/4980553-miike">Miike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4980553-miike?shelf=travel-literature-classics">travel-literature-classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3203819585" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11565563585115994300">This is a very objective account of an embassy sent from the Abbasid Caliph of Baghdad to instruct the (Volga)Bulgars in matters of Islam. The journey takes in some of the most noteable tribes of the 11th century north of the Caspian and Black seas. He travels well into Russia which was in its infancy. He also travels across the Tundra to visit other semi nomadic tribes.<br/><br/>The account is very detailed and doesn&apos;t belittle or pour scorn upon other races - common at the time. It was fascinating to re</span>
  <span id="freeText11565563585115994300" style="display:none">This is a very objective account of an embassy sent from the Abbasid Caliph of Baghdad to instruct the (Volga)Bulgars in matters of Islam. The journey takes in some of the most noteable tribes of the 11th century north of the Caspian and Black seas. He travels well into Russia which was in its infancy. He also travels across the Tundra to visit other semi nomadic tribes.<br /><br />The account is very detailed and doesn't belittle or pour scorn upon other races - common at the time. It was fascinating to read about the Viking burial and some of their customs which seem so alien both today, and even more so back then.<br /><br />The introduction is a welcome account of the traveller, although not much is known about him. There are also several accounts from the Arab world about the various peoples of Europe. I feel like these collection eventually became Geography as we know it.<br /><br />I'd recommend this to those who enjoy Herodotus and the Travels of Ibn Battutah.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11565563585115994300" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


