<div id="review_884180231" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/884180231" />
    <a title="Simon Jones" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10528584-simon-jones"><img alt="Simon Jones" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442634993p2/10528584.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/884180231?book_show_action=true">Mar 17, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simon Jones" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simon Jones" href="/user/show/10528584-simon-jones">Simon Jones</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer884180231" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15915465962157876147">This book actually comprises an extensive collection of accounts by Arabic writers of journeys in the lands of the north of which ibn Fadlan&apos;s is the longest. It dispels some misconceptions by showing how interconnected the early Medieval world was through trade and diplomacy and how open minded and curious Muslims of the period could be about the cultures around them. The writings contain both observations of the everyday life of the peoples of the north and tales of the fantastical inhabitants</span>
  <span id="freeText15915465962157876147" style="display:none">This book actually comprises an extensive collection of accounts by Arabic writers of journeys in the lands of the north of which ibn Fadlan's is the longest. It dispels some misconceptions by showing how interconnected the early Medieval world was through trade and diplomacy and how open minded and curious Muslims of the period could be about the cultures around them. The writings contain both observations of the everyday life of the peoples of the north and tales of the fantastical inhabitants of Gog and Magog who dwell beyond a wall of iron and brass erected by Alexander. The travels undertaken would still be incredible journeys today. At the time for men from the warm climate of the Middle East the frozen wastes must have seemed as alien as another planet.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15915465962157876147" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


