  <span id="freeText1588845462599667003" style="display:none">Fascinating insight into the medieval Arab mind. It not only tells of Ibn Fadlan’s explorations but also several other geographers’, government officers’ and merchants’ recollections in trans-Caucus Europe and Europe itself. At a time when Tuchman is writing about, A World Lit Only by Fire, here are these people plying the trade routes and seas of Europe and Asia, expanding their knowledge and horizons, as well as claiming fairy tales as real (Gog and Magog, e.g.). And yet with all the wonders they DID behold, who could blame them for some misperceptions.</span>
